==Latin==
===Etymology===
# '''[[Anno]]''' is the [[ablative]] of '''[[annus]]''' (''[[year]])''
# '''Domini''' is the [[genitive]] of '''[[Dominus]]''' (''the [[Lord]]'')

===Expression===
'''Anno Domini'''

# in the year of the Lord, that is, a year of the [[Common Era]], often abbreviated [[AD|A.D.]] or [[AD]], though it is becoming more common to use the nonreligious [[CE]] (which is also more precise, as Jesus was actually born around 6 [[BCE]]).

==== Translations ====
* [[Czech]]:    Léta Páně ''or'' roku Páně (''abbr.'' l.P., r.P., A.D.)
* {{msg:fi}}:   Herran vuonna
* [[French]]:   Année du Seigneur (''abbr.'' A.D.)
* [[German]]:   Jahr des Herrn (''abbr.'' A.D.)
* [[Russian]]: [[после]] [[рождество|Рождества]] [[Христов|Христова]] (pósle Roždestvá Xristóva) (''abbr.'' [[после Р. Хр.]])
* [[Slovak]]:  [[rok#Slovak|roku Pána]] ''or'' [[Anno Domini#Latin|Anno Domini]] (''abbr.'' r.P., A.D.)
* [[Polski]]:   Język Łaciński (''abbr.'' A.D.)

